public class Solution {
    public boolean isPowerOfThree(int n) {
        return n > 0 && (n & (n - 1)) == 0 && (n & 0xAAAAAAAA) == 0;
    }
}
```
Explanation:
* The first condition `n > 0` ensures that the input is non-negative.
* The second condition `(n & (n - 1)) == 0` checks if n is a multiple of 3. If it is, then n - 1 will also be a multiple of 3, and the result of `n & (n - 1)` will be 0.
* The third condition `(n & 0xAAAAAAAA) == 0` checks if the third bit of n, which is the least significant bit, is 0. This is a quick check for whether n is a power of 3, as any odd number (including 1 and 2) has a 1 in the least significant bit, while any even number has a 0 in the least significant bit.
Therefore, if all these conditions are satisfied, then n is a power of three, otherwise it is not.

